  toolUrl="https://oortcraft.dev/tools/csv-to-json"
  faq={[
    { question: 'What delimiters are supported?', answer: 'The converter automatically detects commas, tabs, semicolons, and pipes. You do not need to specify the delimiter manually.' },
    { question: 'What does the Header Row option do?', answer: 'When Header Row is enabled, the first row of your CSV is treated as field names and each subsequent row becomes a JSON object with those keys. When disabled, each row is output as an array of values.' },
    { question: 'Is my data safe?', answer: 'Yes. All conversion happens entirely in your browser using the PapaParse library. No data is sent to any server.' },
    { question: 'What happens if a field value contains a comma?', answer: 'PapaParse correctly handles quoted fields. As long as the value is wrapped in double quotes in the CSV — which is standard RFC 4180 behavior from Excel and Google Sheets — commas inside values are treated as part of the string, not as delimiters.' },
    { question: 'What does Type Inference do?', answer: 'When enabled, the converter automatically converts numeric strings to JSON numbers, "true"/"false" strings to JSON booleans, and empty fields to null. Disable it to keep every value as a string.' },
    { question: 'How do I handle a UTF-8 BOM at the start of my CSV?', answer: 'Files exported from Excel often begin with a hidden UTF-8 BOM character (EF BB BF). PapaParse strips the BOM automatically, so the first column header will not have a stray character prepended to it.' },
